"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-the-art-of-the-200-noah-lyles-technique-paris-olympics-gabby-thomas\", \"text\": \"PARIS \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 Sure, he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s biased. But, as Michael Johnson\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094200-meter artist and the event\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s world record holder for 13 years\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094notes, that doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t make him wrong. The 200, he argues, forms an ideal blend of sprint poetry, combining power, speed and endurance.\\u00c2  It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s tactical and strategic, but only briefly, at one or two points in any race. It requires \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cdifferent energy systems than the 100,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he says, which requires more endurance work in training and speed that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s stillblurfast. The 200 is precision. It involves form, technique, horsepower and split-second decisions made at top speed. The strategy can change depending on which lane a competitor is in. The 200-meter race is part 100, part 400; brains and muscle equally important.\\u00c2  Before he broke the world record in the 200, Johnson primarily trained for the 400-meter run. More typically, 100-meter specialists extend their power into twice the distance. Many still struggle to adjust. They typically need to add endurance, along with understanding that they cannot sprint as fast they can in a straight line for twice the distance. They must decide, Johnson says, where \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cthey want to put most of their speed, most of their energy.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBut some people can run it all out, like I could, because of my 400-meter background and base,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Johnson says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBut also because I had extraordinary speed.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d He says that last part dispassionately, because it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s true, and it doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t sound like bragging.  There\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s an art to this race. Most typically it centers on decisions, many made in the precious seconds spent navigating the turn. In most world-class competitions, the best 200 artists will make one technical decision, maybe two. Some are already better curve runners, and they will deploy more energy as the race turns, attempting to remain near or ahead of the pack. Others should be considered straightaway specialists, and they will blaze from the starting blocks, conserve as much energy as possible through the turn and then hit max velocity toward the finish line. By the time they get there, Johnson says, the race is over.  Every second matters, as does every strategic decision, every technical movement, every step on the purple track at Stade de France. Those 200-meter savants must understand themselves, as athletes, what they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re capable of and what their competitors can do. The 200, he says, is trial and error\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cerror, at this level, means losses.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  In the coming days in Paris, the art will take center stage in both the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s and women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 200-meter competitions. Noah Lyles\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094owner of the fourth-best 200 time ever, 0.01 ahead of Johnson\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s former world record\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094will take aim at the current mark, set by Jamaica\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Usain Bolt in 2009. He\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll need to shave 0.13 seconds off his best time, 19.31 seconds. He\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll compete against a field of elite sprinters\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and against that clock.  In the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s final, American Gabby Thomas is now the gold-medal favorite, after two-time reigning 200-meter world championShericka Jackson of Jamaica pulled outof the semifinal heats right before the race. Thomas had never defeated Jackson in the 200.\\u00c2  All understand the art that Johnson is describing. Lyles, in fact, released a video on YouTube in June 2023. It runs for more than 10 minutes. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s equally informative and hilarious. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s technical, the art of the 200 broken into individual components.  This, because he is Lyles, is how it starts:So,first things first,the 200?It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a beautiful woman.You gotta treat it like such.It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not the 100.It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not hard.It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not aggressive.It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s finesse.It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s pretty.It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s sexy.  Each component, added up, begins to prove his points. Lyles doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t care which way any sprinter points their starting blocks. He prefers straight ahead; not in, toward the turn, or out, toward the stands. But that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a choice where only personal preference matters. He wants his body to shoot forward, straight ahead, for the first few steps. After those, he gauges where he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s sprinting in his lane\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094in the middle, always, is the ideal.  Past 10 meters, he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s driving, legs churning, slowly \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cputting more force into the ground.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Around 20 meters, his body, hips and chest slowly begin to rise. No jerking, hence the ramp up.  After 30 meters, his hips come underneath him, his chest rises and his shoulders remain forward, as he drives down the track. At that point, he wants to be standing up, raising his knees high and stamping them right back down on the track like pistons. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cPushing your momentum down the track, almost as if, like, you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re falling,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he says in the video.  He gauges, again, his placement within his lane. If he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s too inside, he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ccutting that stride\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d too much, losing energy and speed. If he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s outside in his lane, he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s running \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ctoo much track.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Think: golfer who bombs drives but elongates holes by spraying them far right or far left.  At 50 meters, he must make \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cprobably the most difficult decision\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d in that race.How am I going to stay in the middle of the lane? Many coaches, he says, tell sprinters to lean in at the turn. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThat\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not accurate.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d He wants to turn his hips, gradually, and the comparison he invokes\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094a car\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s headlights\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094makes his point easy to understand, even though he calls them \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009clight beams.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d He holds both hands near his hips to demonstrate. Lean and those light beams point right, toward the stands. Gradually turn the hips and they point the same way as the body.  At 75 meters, maybe 80, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s time to start putting power into the ground, as you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re coming out of this turn,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIf you let up, in this part of the turn, you will not get the effect of all the work you did back there.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Another check of lane positioning. Then, more power, more speed. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSo we can continue to have that energy that we built up, flowing with us, going down the track. Now, this is where you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re going to feel the best momentum.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  As the turn gives way to the straightway, the final sprint toward the finish line, Lyles says many athletes \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009crelease\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d their body, meaning they start to relax. This can push their momentum outside of their lane, or force them to \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ccut\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d the turn at too drastic of an angle, slowing the very momentum they just created. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAnd, because you made that move down [on the transition from turn to straightaway], the track is gonna spit you out, almost like a slingshot. Think of NASCAR. They go up high on the hill, and they come back down. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the exact feeling you\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re gonna feel.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Interestingly, Lyles breaks the 200 into two, separate 100-meter aims. At 30 meters of the second 100, he says, it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s time to commit\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094to body position, to knees hammering into the track, to keeping those shoulders forward. If those go back, energy escapes upward, unnecessarily. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m gonna ask you: what\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s your favorite cloud? And, if you tell me, you failed.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  At 180 meters, mental focus becomes paramount. Sprinters must follow what their coaches taught them, as close as possible to their chosen ideal form. In all likelihood, their top-end speed is gone. They have two choices: hold it, or slowly begin to slow. Even then, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt needs to look pretty, he says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cAgain, the 200 needs to be finessed.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Finally, the dip. Not too early. Not too late. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThe very two last meters,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Lyles says.  That\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s the art, his version, one that Al Joyner\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094the longtime, respected track coach\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094understands well. His late wife, Florence Griffith-Joyner, still holds the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 200-meter world record (21.34 seconds), set at the Seoul Olympics in 1988. The women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s race, he says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cwill be amazing, ridiculous, because they\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099resoready.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Thomas, her mother Jennifer Randall says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cwas born athletic.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d She took up soccer, karate, softball, lacrosse, golf and tennis. Even as a toddler, when Thomas scampered down a hallway, mom says it appeared as if \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cshe was floating on air.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSuperfast,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Randall says, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ceven then.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Thomas does a million things, impacts thousands of people and runs really fast while balancingan unfathomable docket of ambition. She went to Harvard, won bronze in the 200 at the Tokyo Games (and gold in the 4X100-meter relay), got her Master\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s degree from Texas, took silver at the most recent world championships, then dominated the U.S. Olympic trials back in June. She\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s famous, smart, fast as hell and nice. But that combination can mask what she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s like on the track, especially in the 200. Summarized, in a word:fierce.  Her best friend, Ngozi Musa, who also ran the 200 and other sprints at Harvard alongside Thomas, says she always saw the smiling speedster precisely that way. In Thomas\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s freshman season, she finished sixth at Olympic trials but came across as polite and lovely afterward. But don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t mistake that bearing for how shefelt. She was pissed.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cShe\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s a force to be reckoned with,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Musa says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSheattacksthe 200.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Johnson, another 200-meter artist, couldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t agree more. He calls Thomas a \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cpeerless competitor, but one of those people who doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t always wear that outside the track and can actually be a normal person.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cYou know, her and Noah are in interesting positions,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he says. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSha\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099Carri [Richardson], too. With each, there is tremendous talent, there is some success, but they haven\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t won the big one, so to speak, yet. That will be on their minds. I was there in 1996, because in \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009992, I was a world champion and heavy favorite to win the 200 at the Olympics, and I didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t win. You don\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t want that to be a burden.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Add that pressure to the art of the 200-meter race. For Lyles, Thomas or anyone else, the hope is that the art will yield one thing: gold.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Greg Bishop is a senior writer for Sports Illustrated who has covered every kind of sport and every major event across six continents for more than two decades. He previously worked for The Seattle Times and The New York Times. He is the co-author of two books: Jim Gray\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s memoir, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTalking to GOATs\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d; and Laurent Duvernay Tardif\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cRed Zone\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d. Bishop has written for Showtime Sports, Prime Video and DAZN, and has been nominated for eight sports Emmys, winning two, both for production. He has completed more than a dozen documentary film projects, with a wide range of duties. Bishop, who graduated from the Newhouse School at Syracuse University, is based in Seattle.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"